327 E. 12 St. Apr 5, 70?
My dear little sister;
I wrote you a few lines on Sabbath when I suppose you were having a pretty rough time.  Hope you are about at your journey's end now.  Wonder how you feel on landing.  Sunday P.M. I felt so uneasy about you whenever the wind blew and the rain poured that I went to see our good Dr.? K had quite a long visit.  He went to see how you were getting along.  Said the see was pretty rough but you wre all safe.  You were lying down had been trying ot read but could not make much of it.

Mon. 6 P.M. June 12
My dear little Sister;
I mailed you a letter early this morn but much send you another post haste with medicine for your cold. I have been feeling uneasy about your thin clothing, especially today as it is quite cool. Cant you buy a flannel wrapper to put on? Get some canton flannel and make you a pair of drawers. Your linen dress will be cool to travel in. Mr. & Mrs. Warren did not call, so it would have availed nothing if we had
